# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-89-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1790-91-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1792–93 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 27, 1792, and September 6, 1793.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 3rd United States Congress convened on December 2, 1793.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the addition of the new state of Kentucky's representatives, and the congressional reapportionment based on the 1790 United States census, the size of the House increased to 105 seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They coincided with the re-election of President George Washington.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] While Washington ran for president as an independent, his followers (more specifically, the supporters of Alexander Hamilton) formed the nation's first organized political party, the Federalist Party, whose members and sympathizers are identified as pro-Administration on this page.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In response, followers of Thomas Jefferson and James Madison created the opposition Democratic-Republican Party, who are identified as anti-Administration on this page.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists promoted urbanization, industrialization, mercantilism, a centralized government, and a broad interpretation of the United States Constitution.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In contrast, the Democratic-Republicans supported the ideal of an agrarian republic made up of self-sufficient farmers and small, localized governments with limited power.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite nearly unanimous support for Washington as a presidential candidate, Jeffersonian ideas edged out Hamiltonian principles at the ballot box for congressional candidates, with the Democratic-Republicans taking 24 seats more than they had prior to the organization of their political movement.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Most of the increase was due to the addition of new seats in Western regions as a result of the 1790 census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Dominated by agrarian culture, these Western territories offered strong support to Democratic-Republican congressional candidates.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As a result, they secured a thin majority in the legislature.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In this period, each state fixed its own date for its congressional election as early as August 1792 (in New Hampshire and Rhode Island) and as late as September 1793 (in Kentucky).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year), but as the first session of Congress typically began in November or December, the elections took place before Congress actually met.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 3rd Congress first met on December 2, 1793.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These were the first elections held after reapportionment following the first census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Thirty-six new seats were added, with 1 state losing 1 seat, 3 states having no change, and the remaining 11 states gaining between 1 and 9 seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was the first apportionment based on actual census data, the apportionment for the 1st and 2nd Congresses being set by the Constitution using estimated populations.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With new seats, due to reapportionment, outlined.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1792 and 1793 during the 2nd and 3rd United States Congresses.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by state then district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut gained two seats in reapportionment following the 1790 census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three special elections followed the 1792 elections in Connecticut after Representatives-elect Sturges and Huntington resigned before the start of Congress and Mitchell was elected to the Senate.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Delaware's apportionment did not change following the 1790 census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As in the 1st and 2nd Congresses, each voter cast votes for two separate candidates, at least one of whom had to be from a different county as the voter.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Georgia's apportionment was decreased from 3 seats to 2 (the only state whose representation decreased after the census).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Georgia switched from separate districts to at-large seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Maryland increased from 6 to 8 representatives after the 1790 census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The previous mixed district/at-large system was replaced with a conventional district system.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, Massachusetts's representation increased from eight to fourteen Representatives and was redistricted into four plural districts, plus a single at-large district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 4th district covered the District of Maine (the modern-day State of Maine).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The plural districts were concurrent tickets rather than a single general ticket, though the 1st and 2nd districts appeared to have also had a general ticket alongside the more specific tickets.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] As before, a majority was required for election, in those districts where a majority was not achieved, additional ballots were required.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Hampshire increased from 3 seats to 4 seats after the 1790 census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, New Jersey's apportionment increased from 4 to 5 seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, New York's congressional delegation grew from 6 to 10.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Three incumbents ran for re-election, two of whom won, and the other three incumbents retired.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the increase following re-apportionment, this left seven open seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Following the 1790 census, North Carolina's apportionment increased from 5 to 10 seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania switched from using districts to electing its representatives on an at-large basis for the 3rd Congress, just as it had done for the 1st Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This would be the last time that Pennsylvania would elect all of its Representatives at-large.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to re-apportionment following the 1790 census, Pennsylvania's delegation increased from 8 representatives to 13.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island gained a second representative from the results of the 1790 census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island did not divide itself into districts, but elected two at-large representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] South Carolina gained one representative as a result of the 1790 census, increasing from 5 to 6.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont had no apportionment in the House of Representatives before 1790 census because it was not admitted to the Union until 1791.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont's election laws at the time required a majority to win election to the House of Representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] If no candidate won a majority, a runoff election was held, which happened in the 1st district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Virginia gained nine representatives from the 1790 census, and in addition, the old 2nd district was lost after its territory became the new State of Kentucky.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1792-93-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were, therefore, ten new districts created for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1794–95 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 25, 1794 (New Hampshire), and September 5, 1795 (Kentucky).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 4th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1795.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held during President George Washington's second term.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 105 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the first election for the House of Representatives with organized political parties, the Democratic-Republican Party, which opposed the incumbent Washington Administration, defeated the pro-administration Federalist Party.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The outgoing speaker, Frederick Muhlenberg, had supported the pro-administration forces during his first two terms, but was elected by a coalition made up mainly of anti-administration members in 1793, and by 1795 he was seen as more favorable to the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite the Democratic-Republican majority, however, Muhlenberg was not re-elected, and was succeeded by Federalist Jonathan Dayton.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 3rd and 4th Congresses in 1794 and 1795.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only two candidates are recorded for Delaware's congressional election in 1794, suggesting that the voting procedure in place for the first three Congresses for two candidates had been changed.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts redistricted between the 3rd and 4th Congress, dividing itself into 14 districts.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 12th-14th districts were in the District of Maine (the modern State of Maine).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Additional ballots were required in five districts due to the majority requirement not being met on the first ballot.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under New Hampshire's electoral laws, a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required for election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only three candidates achieved a majority, and so a run-off election was held for the fourth seat.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, but were later numbered retroactively.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania once again divided itself into districts instead of electing representatives at-large, as it had for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The state divided intself into 12 districts, one of which (the 4th) had two seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania would continue to use one or more plural districts until 1842.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Electoral data are only available for the 1st and 5th district of South Carolina's 6 districts at the time of the elections of 1794.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representative-elect Barnwell of the 2nd district declined to serve.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A special election was held to fill the resulting vacancy, electing Wade Hampton (Democratic-Republican).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a majority for election to Congress, with a second election to be held if the first did not return a majority.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Run-off elections were required in both districts.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1796–97 United States House of Representatives elections** took place in the various states between August 12, 1796 (in North Carolina), and October 15, 1797 (in Tennessee).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The size of the House increased to 106 seats after Tennessee became the 16th U.S. state to join the union.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The first session of the 5th United States Congress was convened on May 15, 1797, at the proclamation of the new President of the United States, John Adams.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since Kentucky and Tennessee had not yet voted, they were unrepresented until the second session began on November 13, 1797.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Gains for the Federalist Party provided the president with a reliable majority in support of his policies.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many of the Federalist pick-ups in Congress came from the former Middle Colonies (New York, Pennsylvania, New Jersey, and Delaware).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New England remained heavily Federalist, whereas the South and West favored Democratic-Republican candidates.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federalist trade and infrastructure policies found widespread approval in the Mid-Atlantic states during this era.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] With the growth of cities in Maryland, Pennsylvania, and New York, government intervention in the interest of industrialization and mercantilism became more attractive to voting citizens in these areas.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 1st session of the 5th Congress ran May 15 – July 10, 1797, before the states of Kentucky and Tennessee had their elections, causing those states to be unrepresented in the 1st session.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted by election date, then by district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 4th Congress in 1796.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 5th Congress in 1797.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Connecticut elected its seven representatives at-large on a general ticket.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Two of the four Democratic-Republicans were replaced by Federalists, bringing the Federalists from a 4–4 split to a 6–2 majority.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts's electoral law required a majority for election, necessitating additional trials in three districts.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1796, New Hampshire had a single at-large district with 4 seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each voter cast 4 votes and a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required to be elected.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Since only three candidates received a majority, a run-off was held between the candidates in fourth and fifth place to fill the remaining seat.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island had an at-large district with two seats, each of which were elected separately.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1796-97-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Due to Vermont's law requiring a majority to secure a congressional seat, the 1st district required three ballots to choose a winner.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1798–99 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 24, 1798, in New York and August 1, 1799, in Tennessee.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives, with some after the official start of the 6th United States Congress on March 4, 1799, but before the start of the first session of this Congress in Philadelphia on December 2, 1799.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These elections were held during President John Adams' term.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] It was the last congressional session before the move to the new capital at Washington, D.C.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 106 seats, representing 16 states.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This resulted in an increased Federalist majority in the House, 60-46 seats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalist party squandered its popularity by passing a series of controversial new laws in the summer of 1798, including the Naturalization Act of 1798 and the Alien and Sedition Acts.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Their passage seriously injured the chances of President Adams and Federalist congressional candidates in the elections of 1800.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The House that met during this Congress would ultimately elect Thomas Jefferson over Aaron Burr in the presidential election of 1800.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1798 and 1799 during the 5th United States Congress and 6th United States Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections are sorted here by date then district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts required a majority for election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This was not met in the 5th district and 7th district necessitating additional ballots in those districts.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Jersey switched to district representation for this election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The districts were not numbered at the time, but are retroactively numbered here as 1–5.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New Jersey would go back to an at-large district the following election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Between the 1796 and 1798 elections, New York re-districted.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This marked the first time that its districts were numbered.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island used at-large districts, but elected the candidates on separate tickets instead of using a general ticket.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1798-99-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Majority vote required to win, necessitating a run-off election in the 1st (Western) district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1800–01 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 29, 1800, and August 1, 1801.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 7th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1801.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held at the same time as the 1800 presidential election, in which Vice President Thomas Jefferson, a Democratic Republican, defeated incumbent President John Adams, a Federalist.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 106 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] These elections resulted in the Democratic-Republicans picking up 22 seats from the Federalists.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] This brought the Democratic-Republicans a solid majority of 68 seats, whereas the Federalists were only able to secure 38.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Many state legislatures also changed to Democratic-Republican control, with the result that many new Democratic-Republicans were voted into the Senate.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The Federalists never again succeeded in gaining a majority of seats in the House of Representatives, and the national Federalist Party disintegrated completely in the early 1820s.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The victory of Jefferson and the Democratic-Republicans can be attributed partially to unpopular policies pursued by the Adams administration, including the Alien and Sedition Acts, which sought to curtail guarantees of freedom of speech and freedom of the press spelled out in the Bill of Rights.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The difference between Federalist policies in support of a strong national government and the Democratic-Republican preference for states' rights played a prominent role in the election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Federal taxation became an issue as Southerners and Westerners rejected federal taxes levied on property.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special elections in 1800 and 1801 during the 6th United States Congress and 7th United States Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Note: Between the two sources used, there is disagreement over the ordering of the candidates.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They are ordered here as Goddard and Talmadge in 8th and 9th place as it is more likely that they'd been at the top of the runners-up given that they were subsequently elected to fill vacancies in the 7th Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts law required a majority for election, which was not met in the 1st and 6th districts, necessitating a second trial.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In 1800, New Jersey returned to its traditional at-large district, continued to use this system to select representatives until it was abolished in 1842, with a single exception in 1813.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Rhode Island switched to a general ticket for its two seats, instead of electing each one separately.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only one candidate received a majority in the 1800 election, requiring an 1801 run-off election to choose a Representative for the second seat.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1800-01-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a candidate to win a majority to take office, necessitating a run-off election in the 2nd (Eastern) district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The **1862–63 United States House of Representatives elections** were held between June 2, 1862, and November 3, 1863, to elect the 184 members and eight non-voting delegates of the House of Representatives.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Republican–Union coalition lost seats but retained an overall majority against the backdrop of the American Civil War.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In the first real test of opposition to the Lincoln administration, the Democratic Party made large gains in these and concurrent elections held in 1862 and 1863 but failed to take control of the House.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Much of the campaign focussed on emancipation and Lincoln's handling of the war.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, weeks before critical races in Indiana, Ohio, Pennsylvania, (October 14) and New York (November 3).
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats denounced emancipation as tyrannical and a threat to white supremacy.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democratic election propaganda charged their opponents with bloodlust and religious fanaticism and made frequent appeals to anti-Black racism.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] While Radical Republicans defended the measure, others felt compelled to distance themselves from the president's policy.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In Indiana and Ohio, the Union Party downplayed the slavery issue.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The issue was particularly troublesome for Unionists in the border states.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kentucky's Union Democratic Party disavowed the proclamation ahead of congressional elections held in August 1863.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In Maryland and Missouri, Unionists welcomed emancipation in principle but divided over questions over gradual versus immediate abolition and the enlistment of Black soldiers.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Other issues impacted the election, including Lincoln's suspension of *habeas corpus*, conscription, and the progress of the war.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Inconclusive Union victories at Antietam, Corinth, and Perryville contributed to a perception that the administration's military strategy was ineffective.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats charged the administration with subordinating the restoration of the Union to the radical social policy of the abolitionist movement.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] During this election, the Republican Party formed a coalition with War Democrats and border state unionists who supported the war effort.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In most states, this coalition was known as the Union Party or as the Republican–Union Party.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In parts of New England and the Upper Midwest, pro-administration candidates still called themselves Republicans.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Missouri Unionists were known as the Emancipation Party and split between Immediate and Gradual Emancipationists during this election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Republican–Union coalition became the basis for the National Union Party which contested the next election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] While contemporary observers interpreted the elections as a "severe reproof" of the administration, the results of the elections were inconclusive.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Democrats flipped more than 30 seats compared to the last election, while Republican–Unionists suffered serious losses across the Lower North.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The strong showing for Union candidates in the border states, however, salvaged the Republican–Unionist majority.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Among the defeated Republican–Unionists was the incumbent speaker of the House of Representatives Galusha A.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Grow, who lost his Pennsylvania district to a Democratic challenger.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] This was the last election in which a sitting speaker of the House was defeated for re-election until 1994, when George Nethercutt defeated Tom Foley in Washington's 5th congressional district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Reapportionment took place following the 1860 United States census.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The 1862 apportionment act increased the size of the House to 241 seats from 233.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Fifty-eight seats were vacant due to secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Three seats were transferred from Virginia to West Virginia following the latter's admission on June 20, 1863.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] One seat was allocated to Nevada upon its admission on October 31, 1864, increasing the size of the House to 242 seats and the number of elected members to 184.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Special elections were held in 1862 and 1863 to fill 12 vacancies in the 37th Congress and four vacancies in the 38th Congress.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Alabama did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Arkansas held no elections in 1862 or 1863 as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Late elections were held in 1864, but the elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] California elected its members on September 2, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Voters chose three members on a statewide general ticket to represent the state's at-large congressional district.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Connecticut elected its members April 6, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Delaware elected its member on November 1, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Florida did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Georgia did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Illinois elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Indiana elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Iowa elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kansas elected its member on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Whereas the Union Party replaced the Republicans in most states during the war, the Kansas Republican Party remained active.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] In a factional schism, opponents of U.S. senator Jim Lane split from the Republican Party in 1862 to form the Union Party with the support of the state's Democrats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Parrott for Congress, was not affiliated with the national Republican–Union coalition and broke apart during the 1864 presidential election.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Kentucky elected its members on August 3, 1863, after the new term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Louisiana held no elections for the 38th Congress in 1862 or 1863 as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Late elections were held on September 5, 1864, but the elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Maine elected its members on September 8, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Maryland elected its members on November 3, 1863, after the new term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Massachusetts elected its members on November 1, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Massachusetts Republicans resisted incorporation into the Union Party in 1861 and 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Conservative Republicans, former Whigs, and Democrats attended the state convention of the Constitutional Union Party which nominated candidates for the upcoming elections.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The convention called itself the People's Party in order to attract votes from Democrats.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Conservative former Whigs and Republicans in the party expressed strong support for the Lincoln administration during the spring and summer under the belief that the president firmly opposed emancipation.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, issued less than two weeks before the state convention met, helped to divide and defeat the new party in its infancy.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Michigan elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] A Democratic proposal for a bipartisan Union ticket was rejected by the Radical leadership of the Michigan Republican Party.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The Democrats went ahead with plans for a Union state convention and called themselves Union Democrats or Fusionists during the campaign in hopes of attracting votes from disaffected Conservative Republicans.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Some conservatives did support the Union ticket, which was disavowed by the Republican state committee.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Minnesota elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Mississippi did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Missouri elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Missouri Unionists contested this election as the Emancipation Party.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] The party was divided ideologically between conservative Claybanks, who favored a plan of gradual emancipation, and radical Charcoals, who supported immediate emancipation.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Louis, Gradual and Immediate Emancipationists ran opposing tickets.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Some sources list the Gradual Emancipation candidates as Republicans; however, the Republican state committee deliberately deemphasized old party labels in its call for the state convention which gave rise to the Emancipation Party.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] Francis Preston Blair Jr., the most prominent leader of the Antebellum Missouri Republican Party, was nominated on the Union Emancipation ticket in Missouri's 1st congressional district and contested the election as a Gradual Emancipationist.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New Hampshire elected its members on March 10, 1863.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p01] New Jersey elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] New York elected its members on November 4, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] North Carolina did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Ohio elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Oregon elected its members on June 2, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Pennsylvania elected its members on October 14, 1862.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Rhode Island elected its members on April 1, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] South Carolina did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Tennessee did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Texas did not hold elections as a result of secession.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Vermont elected its members on September 1, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The Restored Government of Virginia held elections in three districts on May 28, 1863, after the term began but before Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The elected members were not seated by the House.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] West Virginia elected its members on October 22, 1863, after the term began but before the Congress convened.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The state and its congressional districts had formed part of Western Virginia before being admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, with the consent of the Restored Government of Virginia.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] The West Virginian members were seated on December 7, 1863.
[src:1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1862-63-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-p02] Wisconsin elected its members on November 4, 1862.
